author: Sherif Tarek
description: The United Nations says nearly 89,000 civilians have fled Sudan’s El-Fasher since a paramilitary group captured the city last month, calling for an immediate ceasefire as the war in the North African country remains unabated for the third year.
title: UN Says 89,000 Fled Sudan’s El-Fasher, Urges Immediate Ceasefire

author: Miles J. Herszenhorn
description: US academic organizations that won a court ruling against the Trump administration for “bullying” international students over their political views by making them leave the country now are asking the judge to go further.
title: Professors Ask Judge to Get Tougher on Trump ‘Bullying’ Students

author: Caitlin Reilly, Erik Wasson, Rachel Cohrs Zhang
description: Expiring Obamacare subsidies face an uphill battle for renewal in the coming weeks as Democrats race against the clock to try to find enough Republicans willing to back an extension.
title: Shutdown Deal Leaves Popular Obamacare Subsidies on Shaky Ground

author: Daniel Flatley
description: President Donald Trump’s idea of mailing $2,000 “dividend” payments from tariffs to US citizens marks a throwback to the stimulus checks distributed during the Covid crisis, with similar economic risks.
title: Trump’s $2,000 Tariff ‘Dividend’ Marks Throwback to Covid Checks

author: Nathan R Dean
description: The Government may reopen by weeks end once the Senate and House vote.
title: What’s Coming Next Now That There’s a Deal to End the Shutdown

author: Ted Mann
description: The decision by a group of Senate Democrats to vote to end the 41-day government shutdown —  after extracting no meaningful concessions from President Donald Trump — has triggered outrage across much of the party.
title: Democrats Trade Election Euphoria for Angst Over Shutdown Deal

author: Josh Wingrove
description: President Donald Trump said he “at some point” would reduce the tariff rate on Indian goods, saying the US was getting “pretty close” to a trade deal with New Delhi.
title: Trump Says Close to India Trade Deal to Bring Tariff Rate Down

author: Martin Z Braun
description: Democratic Mayor-Elect Zohran Mamdani appointed a seasoned bureaucrat to manage New York City’s day-to-day operations and roughly $120 billion budget.
title: Mamdani Appoints Budget Guru Dean Fuleihan as First Deputy Mayor

author: Salma El Wardany
description: A son of former Libyan dictator Muammar Qaddafi was freed in Lebanon, almost a decade after he was detained on accusations that he had a role in the 1970s disappearance of a prominent Islamic cleric during his father’s reign.
title: Qaddafi’s Son Hannibal Freed From Decade of Detention in Lebanon

author: Eliyahu Kamisher
description: Christine Pelosi said she’s running for a California state senate seat, passing up the contest to replace her mother, former Speaker Nancy Pelosi, in the US Congress.
title: Nancy Pelosi’s Daughter Picks State Senate Bid Over US House Run

author: Gregory Korte
description: The US president’s power to pardon is both one of the most absolute and misunderstood provisions of the Constitution. Rooted in the “prerogative of mercy” of English kings dating back to the seventh century, America’s founders wanted a robust pardon power to allow “easy access to exceptions in favor of unfortunate guilt” by the justice system, as Alexander Hamilton wrote.
title: Trump’s Pardon of Giuliani: How Presidential Clemency Powers Work

author: Maggie Eastland
description: The Trump administration has cemented one of its key concessions from the latest US-China trade truce by formally delaying an export control rule designed to crack down on shipments to companies that are majority-backed by blacklisted firms.
title: US Formally Delays Affiliates Rule for One Year in US-China Pact

author: Iain Marlow
description: The US military destroyed two alleged drug-trafficking boats in the eastern Pacific Ocean on Sunday, killing six more people in the latest attack in the eastern Pacific.
title: US Strikes Two More ‘Narco’ Boats in Pacific, Killing Six

author: Olivia Solon, Rose Henderson
description: The BBC scandal that triggered the resignations of two top executives hands more fuel to those who’ve assailed its business model and want to see the public service broadcaster lose its special status in the UK.
title: BBC Bias Scandal Puts Future Funding of Broadcaster at Risk

author: Bastian Benrath-Wright, Hugo Miller, Fabienne Kinzelmann
description: Switzerland is close to securing a 15% tariff on its exports to the US, in what would be a relief for the country after it was hit with a punishing 39% levy in August, according to people familiar with the matter.
title: Switzerland Moves Close to Securing Improved 15% Tariff Deal

author: Alex Vasquez, Gonzalo Soto
description: President Claudia Sheinbaum’s plan to impose steep tariffs on Chinese imports has been delayed until at least December as mounting opposition from Mexico’s private sector and even members of the ruling party stalls congressional debate, according to lawmakers and business leaders.
title: Sheinbaum’s China Tariffs Plan Meets Business, Party Backlash

author: Josh Wingrove, Kate Sullivan
description: Syria will join a US-led coalition to defeat the Islamic State, according to a US official, as President Ahmed al-Sharaa meets with US President Donald Trump at the White House.
title: Syrian Leader to Join Fight on Islamic State as He Meets Trump

author: Skylar Woodhouse
description: President Donald Trump urged air traffic controllers who have missed work during the government shutdown to return to their posts, threatening to withhold pay for those who do not show up as travelers in the US face flight delays and cancellations.
title: Trump Warns Air Traffic Controllers to Work or Get ‘Docked’

author: William Standring, Lucy White
description: Nigel Farage accused the government of trampling on small businesses as he sought to increase pressure on UK Chancellor of the Exchequer Rachel Reeves ahead of her budget.
title: UK Is No Country for Small Firms, Farage Says Ahead of Budget

author: Greg Stohr
description: The Trump administration said the US Supreme Court should keep $4 billion in food aid on hold, vowing to keep waging a legal fight to reduce or delay assistance to millions of low-income families.
title: Trump Officials Vow to Renew Food-Aid Fight at Supreme Court

author: Erik Wasson, Steven T. Dennis, Jamie Tarabay
description: The US government is still days away from reopening as the Senate winds its way through potentially time-consuming procedures and House members travel back to Washington to vote for the first time since Sept. 19.
title: US Shutdown Still Days Away From Ending Even as Senate Deal Moves Ahead

author: Stephan Kueffner
description: More than two dozen inmates were found hanged in a prison in southwestern Ecuador just hours after a deadly riot, according to the prison service.
title: Ecuador Prison Violence Spirals, With Dozens of Inmates Hanged

author: Isobel Finkel
description: UK Chancellor of the Exchequer Rachel Reeves indicated the Labour Party may be preparing to break manifesto commitments not to raise taxes, as she looks ahead to what she called a “difficult” budget.
title: Reeves Provides Strongest Hint Yet of Plans to Raise UK Taxes

author: Swati Gupta, Santosh Kumar
description: Eight people died and several were injured in an explosion near the historic Red Fort in India’s capital New Delhi, one of the most crowded areas in the city.
title: New Delhi Explosion Kills Eight People, Leaves Several Hurt

author: Derek Wallbank, Skylar Woodhouse
description: President Donald Trump pardoned dozens of Republicans, including Rudy Giuliani, who aided his effort to overturn the results of the 2020 election, a largely symbolic gesture toward some of his top allies.
title: Trump Pardons Giuliani, Others Over Efforts to Reverse 2020 Loss

author: Ewa Krukowska
description: A European Union parliamentary committee is set to recommend the bloc takes on a new emissions-reduction goal, a key step on the path to net zero by midcentury.
title: EU Parliament Panel Set to Back 2040 Emissions-Cut Target of 90%

author: Greg Stohr
description: The US Supreme Court declined to reconsider its 2015 decision legalizing same-sex marriage, turning away an appeal by a former Kentucky county clerk who was ordered to pay $360,000 for defying the ruling.
title: Supreme Court Rejects Bid to Overturn Same-Sex Marriage Rights

author: Greg Stohr
description: The US Supreme Court agreed to decide whether federal ballots can be counted if they arrive after Election Day in a politically charged clash that will decide the fate of about 30 state laws in advance of next year’s pivotal midterm vote.
title: Mail-Ballot Deadline Clash Draws Review From Supreme Court

author: Bastian Benrath-Wright
description: Switzerland will rejoin a roster of European Union-related programs including Horizon Europe after a deal signed on Monday that could unlock a wave of research funding from the bloc.
title: Switzerland Wins Horizon Europe Accord in Payoff for EU Deal

author: Gaspard Sebag
description: Former French President Nicolas Sarkozy will be released from his “nightmare” in a French jail just 20 days into a five-year sentence for his role in an alleged electoral funding conspiracy linked to the late Libyan leader Moammar Qaddafi’s regime.
title: Sarkozy Freed After Just 20 Days in Jail Over Qaddafi Conspiracy

author: Paul Vecchiatto
description: South Africa’s Fisheries, Forestry and Environment Minister Dion George looks likely to lose his post after his party, the Democratic Alliance, proposed that he be replaced by its spokesman, Willie Aucamp.
title: South African Environment Minister Dion George Set to Lose His Post

author: Marton Eder
description: Harald Mahrer, president of the Austrian Federal Economic Chambers and one of the nation’s most influential public figures, quit his central-bank post after an outcry over salaries at his business lobby.
title: Top Austrian Power Broker Steps Down From Central-Bank Role

author: Yoshiaki Nohara, Sakura Murakami, Takashi Umekawa
description: Japanese Prime Minister Sanae Takaichi aims to use her first stimulus package to jump-start the economy and initiate a new growth strategy through investment in key industries.
title: Japan’s Takaichi Eyes Stimulus Package to Jump-Start Growth Plan

author: Marton Kasnyik
description: Shares of Hungarian refiner Mol Nyrt. rose after Prime Minister Viktor Orban secured an exemption from US sanctions on Russian oil — which is key to the company’s operations.
title: Mol Rises After Hungary Wins US Exemption on Russian Sanctions

author: Ellen Huet
description: OneTaste’s former leaders were once the seeming vanguard of women’s empowerment, but an excerpt from Ellen Huet’s book Empire of Orgasm shows how they became convicted felons who wouldn’t mind a Trump pardon.
title: Sex, Power and the Downfall of the Orgasmic Meditation Cult

author: Carolina Gonzalez, Vinicius Andrade
description: Investors have largely priced in a political swing to the right in Chile, yet traders and analysts see further gains if that market-friendly shift is consolidated in Sunday’s general elections.
title: A Trader’s Guide to Navigating General Elections in Chile

author: S'thembile Cele
description: With Putin a no-show and Xi yet to confirm, the BRICS contingent may be in short supply.
title: South Africa’s G-20 Is Looking Threadbare With Trump Snub

author: Tom Rees, Greg Ritchie
description: The UK plans to temporarily impose strict caps on stablecoin holdings, including a £20,000 ($26,350) limit for individuals, and allow issuers to have as much as 60% of the backing assets in short-term government debt.
title: UK to Limit Stablecoin Holdings in Tougher Regime Than US

author: Mark Niquette, Lauren Dezenski
description: President Donald Trump has been back in office long enough for Americans to expect at least glimmers of the economic golden age he promised. Instead, warning signals are flashing.
title: It’s Trump’s Economy Now and Americans Don’t Seem to Love It

author: Colum Murphy
description: China said it complained to Europe’s legislature over a speech Taiwanese Vice President Hsiao Bi-khim gave to a group of its members, a spat that comes with tensions already heightened over trade and other issues.
title: China Complains to European Parliament Over Taiwan VP’s Speech

author: Daryna Krasnolutska, Olesia Safronova
description: Ukrainian anti-graft agencies said they’re conducting “a large-scale operation” to investigate corruption in the energy sector, as businesses and households wrestle with the impact of the latest Russian attacks on the country’s power system.
title: Ukraine Anti-Graft Agencies Probe Corruption in Energy Sector

author: Colum Murphy, Alan Wong
description: China added more than a dozen fentanyl precursors to a list of controlled exports to the US, Mexico and Canada, in an apparent move to implement commitments made in a trade deal reached between Xi Jinping and Donald Trump last month.
title: China Curbs Drug Precursors to North America After US Trade Deal

author: Helen Nyambura
description: Tanzanian authorities ordered the arrest of 10 senior leaders of the main opposition party, part of a crackdown in the wake of deadly protests over the east African nation’s disputed election.
title: Tanzania Targets Top Opposition Leaders in Post-Vote Crackdown

author: Patpicha Tanakasempipat
description: Thailand’s Prime Minister Anutin Charnvirakul has threatened to derail a fragile peace deal with Cambodia — signed just last month — after a land-mine explosion injured two Thai soldiers near their shared border.
title: Land Mine Blast Puts Fragile Thai-Cambodian Peace Deal at Risk

author: Peter Blumberg
description: A US appeals court refused to pause a judge’s order requiring the Trump administration to fully fund November food-aid benefits to 42 million eligible Americans.
title: Trump Administration Loses Bid to Limit Food Aid Funding for Now

author: Sakura Murakami, James Mayger
description: Japanese Prime Minister Sanae Takaichi on Monday defended her description of a conflict over Taiwan as potentially amounting to an existential risk for Japan after a Chinese diplomat accused her of meddling in Beijing’s internal affairs.
title: Japan’s Takaichi Defends Taiwan Remarks After Chinese Criticism

author: Bhaskar Dutta
description: Emerging-market Asian stocks rose as optimism over an end to the longest-ever US government shutdown boosted risk appetite.
title: EM Stocks, Currencies Gain as US Shutdown Approaches End

author: Steven T. Dennis, Erik Wasson
description: Democrats entered the shutdown seeking to renew tax credits to stave off insurance premium price hikes and to show voters they have the stomach for hardball negotiations in President Donald Trump’s Washington.
title: Democrats Concede Shutdown Fight Without Health Care Win in Hand

author: Chandra Asmara
description: Indonesia’s President Prabowo Subianto has named former authoritarian ruler Suharto a national hero, a symbolic move that’s reignited a long-running debate in the world’s third-largest democracy over its dark past and human-rights record.
title: Prabowo Honors Suharto as National Hero, Stirring Old Wounds

author: Joe Lovinger
description: Texas Governor Greg Abbott said he’ll run for reelection, unveiling an unprecedented bid for a fourth term leading the second-largest state in the US.
title: Greg Abbott Unveils Bid for Record Fourth Term as Texas Governor

author: Steven T. Dennis, Erik Wasson
description: The record-breaking US government shutdown is nearing an end after a group of moderate Senate Democrats agreed to support a deal to reopen the government and fund some departments and agencies for the next year, people familiar with the talks said.
title: US Shutdown Nears End as Senate Democrats Agree to Funding Deal
